{"x0": 9.07, "y0": 39.53, "x1": 14.57, "y1": 43.42}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 11.91, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 13.37}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 16.05, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 17.5}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 20.17, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 21.62}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 26.37, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 27.82}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 30.49, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 31.94}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 34.62, "x1": 11.13, "y1": 36.07}], "full_text": "Radiology\nHow does MR work?\nMRI uses a strong magnetic field and radio waves to create detailed images by\naligning the body's hydrogen protons, causing them to spin.\nWhen a radiofrequency pulse is applied, the protons are knocked out of alignment\nand then release energy as they realign with the magnetic field.\nThis released energy is measured by the MRI machine's coils, and different tissues\nreturn to their original state at different rates, which allows the system to\ndifferentiate between them and create an image.\nProtons (nuclei of hydrogen atoms) placed in a strong magnetic field are excited by\na radio-frequency pulse, then allowed to loose energy.\nThe loss of gained energy occurs either to the surrounding matrix (T1) or through\ninteraction between each other (T2).\nThe loss of energy is measured and used to produce images.\nAdvantages of MR\n1. No ionizing radiation.\n2. High contrast resolution.\n3. Good spatial resolution.\n4. Multiplanar capabilities.\n5. Multi weighted sequences:\na) Fluid attenuation (FLAIR).\nb) Fat suppression (STIR).\nc) Diffusion weighted (DWI), Diffusion Tensor (DTI).\nd) Functional MR (fMR: BOLD).\ne) Spectroscopy (MRS).\nWhen to use MRI?\n1. Soft tissue imaging for the brain and spinal cord.\n2. Detecting and characterizing intra-cranial or intra-spinal lesions/tumors.\n3. Acute ischemia\n4. White matter diseases, e.g. vasculitis, demyelinating diseases.\n33"}